@page "/about"

<PageTitle>About — Panchikaran</PageTitle>

<div class="page-header">
    <h1>About This Text</h1>
    <p class="page-subtitle">सार्थ, सटीक पंचीकरण — मराठी</p>
</div>

<div class="about-content">

    <div class="about-block">
        <h2>The Original Text</h2>
        <p>
            <strong>Panchikaran</strong> (पंचीकरण) is a foundational prakarana grantha (introductory treatise)
            of Advaita Vedānta, attributed to <strong>Adi Shankaracharya</strong> (c. 788–820 CE),
            the great systematizer of Advaita philosophy.
        </p>
        <p>
            The text takes its name from the central process it describes: <em>Panchikaran</em> — the fivefold
            combination (पंचीकरण) of the five subtle elements (Tanmatras) into the five gross elements
            (Sthula Mahābhūtas) that constitute the physical universe.
        </p>
        <p>
            Unlike the major Upanishads, Panchikaran is compact and systematic — designed as a clear
            introduction for the earnest student of Vedānta before approaching the larger texts.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="about-block">
        <h2>This Marathi Edition</h2>
        <p>
            This digital edition is based on <em>Sartha Satik Panchikaran — Marathi</em>
            (सार्थ, सटीक पंचीकरण — मराठी), published by <strong>Tukaram Book Depot</strong>,
            Mumbai (3rd edition, August 2008).
        </p>
        <p>
            The commentary was made in the tradition of <strong>Brahmanishtha Shriramguru</strong>,
            with the lineage tracing through Shrimad Shankaracharya →
            Sridakshiṇananda Sarasvati → Sadeshika-shishya Jayakrishnaji.
        </p>
        <p>
            The Marathi translation makes the dense Sanskrit text accessible through:
        </p>
        <ul class="about-list">
            <li>Verse-by-verse Marathi commentary (Tikā)</li>
            <li>Systematic tables (Koshtaka) mapping the principles of each body</li>
            <li>Six illustrative analogies (Dṛṣṭānta) with their philosophical resolutions</li>
            <li>Detailed descriptions of all Nine Processes (Prakriyas)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="about-block">
        <h2>The Central Teaching</h2>
        <div class="mahavakya-display">
            <p class="shloka-text large">तत्त्वमसि</p>
            <p class="shloka-trans">Tat Tvam Asi — That Thou Art</p>
            <p class="shloka-source">Chandogya Upanishad 6.8.7</p>
        </div>
        <p>
            All of Panchikaran builds toward a single recognition: the individual self (Jiva),
            though it appears bound and limited, is in its deepest nature identical with Brahman —
            the infinite, self-luminous, non-dual Pure Consciousness.
        </p>
        <p>
            The description of Panchikaran — the process by which Brahman appears as the universe —
            is not mere cosmology. It is the map that allows the student to trace the universe back
            to its source, and recognize that source as their own Self.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="about-block">
        <h2>The Four Great Statements (Mahāvākyas)</h2>
        <div class="mahavakya-grid">
            <div class="mv-card">
                <div class="mv-text">प्रज्ञानं ब्रह्म</div>
                <div class="mv-trans">Consciousness is Brahman</div>
                <div class="mv-source">Aitareya Upanishad (Rigveda)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="mv-card">
                <div class="mv-text">अहं ब्रह्मास्मि</div>
                <div class="mv-trans">I am Brahman</div>
                <div class="mv-source">Brihadaranyaka Upanishad (Yajurveda)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="mv-card">
                <div class="mv-text">तत्त्वमसि</div>
                <div class="mv-trans">That Thou Art</div>
                <div class="mv-source">Chandogya Upanishad (Samaveda)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="mv-card">
                <div class="mv-text">अयमात्मा ब्रह्म</div>
                <div class="mv-trans">This Self is Brahman</div>
                <div class="mv-source">Mandukya Upanishad (Atharvaveda)</div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="about-block">
        <h2>This Website</h2>
        <p>
            This Blazor Web App was built to make the teachings of Panchikaran interactively accessible —
            with an explorable table of contents, an interactive visualization of the Panchikaran process,
            a searchable Sanskrit glossary, concept cards, and the six illustrative analogies.
        </p>
        <p>
            Built with <strong>ASP.NET Core Blazor Web App (.NET 8)</strong> using Auto interactivity
            (Server + WebAssembly) with global render mode.
        </p>
    </div>

</div>
